AGI - The glacial caps of Patagonia are the largest of all the southern hemisphere, excluding Antarctica, and cover part of the Andes chain in Argentina and Chile. Although they extend for about 16 thousand square kilometers they are still little known. A new study, published in the magazine 'Communications Earth &amp; Environment', of the group 'Nature', reassessed the volume of the two ice fields of Patagonia using geophysical methods of remote sensing and satellite images. These caps have 40 times more ice than all glaciers in the European Alps and the study showed how vulnerable they are to the effects of climate change.
&nbsp;
The international research group, led by Johannes Furst of the Geographic Institute of the University of Erlangen-Norimberga, and composed of several universities and research institutes, including the National Institute of Oceanography and Experimental Geophysics-Ogs, rated that the glacial caps of Patagonia contain 5,351 cubic kilometers of ice (referred to the year 2000) and in some glacial valleys.
&nbsp;
"We knew very little of Patagonia's caps, two huge glacial fields of the size of just below that of Veneto - explains Emanuele Lodolo, researcher of the National Institute of Oceanography and Experimental Geophysics-Ogs - until now we had not much information about their thickness and the volumes involved, despite these extend, respectively, for about 130 and 350 kilometers in the northern and southern cap, and with widths exceeding 60 kilometers".
&nbsp;
The analysis of satellite maps and geophysical information acquired in the study showed that some glaciers in the eastern flank sector of the cap are backwards of several kilometers in recent decades, while others have remained essentially stable. These dynamics are influenced by morphology and depth of lake basins in which they converge: where they are deeper, the backwardness of the glacial fronts was more consistent and fast.
&nbsp;
"While glaciers in the European Alps rarely have a speed of more than 200 meters a year, most of the Patagonia glaciers exceed this speed and some reach a speed of several kilometers a year. Only the glaciers that originate from the great peaks of Greenland and the Western Antarctica have so high values of speed of flow - explains Emanuele Lodolo - the caps of Patagonia lose every year on average a meter of ice thickness and this has significant effects not only on the water resources of the region, but on all the surrounding ecosystem. All this fuels great concerns, also linked to the increased risk of extreme weather events that have hit the region hard in recent years," concludes the researcher.&nbsp;

