AGI - The war of drones between Russia and Ukraine continues, aimed at the respective energy infrastructure. Almost a dozen people were injured in a Russian attack on the south of Ukraine, while a fire broke out in a large Russian power plant after an attack of Ukrainian drones on the area. Kiev reported that Russian drones hit the southern regions of Mykolaiv and Odessa.
&nbsp;
During the night targeted attacks on energy plants > behind the front lines continued. "The enemy attacked the Odessa region with drones once again," explained Governor Oleg Kiper in a post on Telegram. "Energy infrastructure has been damaged and there is no electricity in some parts of the city," he added.
&nbsp;
About 11 people were injured in the southern city of Mykolaiv after an attack by Russian drones, reported the Ukrainian army spokesman Nataliya Gumenyuk in an interview with the national TV.
&nbsp;
In Russia, a fire broke out in an electric power plant in the southern region of Rostov. Two power units in the Novocherkassk power plant - one of the largest in the south-west of Russia - were put out of use, he still wrote on Telegram Governor Vasily Golubev. The Rostov region borders Ukraine and the regional capital is home to Moscow military command. "There were no victims. The causes of the fire are being investigated," Golubev said. Videos are circulated on social media that show some explosions near the power station.
&nbsp;
"Russia launched almost 190 missiles, 140 Shahed drones and 700 air bombs against Ukraine in the last week," said President Volodymyr Zelensky> on Sunday in his evening speech to the nation. The president explained that they are in progress, reports The Kyiv Indipendent, restoration works after the large-scale attack on the energy infrastructures of March 22.
&nbsp;
In some regions electricity supply has been restored. While more than 200,000 houses still remain without electricity in the city of Kharkiv and in a Kharkiv Oblast district. Zelensky thanked all Ukraine's defence and security forces for their efforts to protect the country.
&nbsp;
The Ukrainian President has therefore reported that he has recently spoken with Spanish Prime Minister Pedro Sanchez> to strengthen Ukraine's air defence system. Russia launched another "massive missile attack and drones" Sunday, targeting critical infrastructure and leaving thousands of people without heating.

